, found worldwide, is represented by 838 extant species, and four fossil species (AntWeb 2016); 25% of the species occur in the Neotropics (
Lattke and Aguirre 2015
). Most species of this genus occur in tropical rainforest, some in grassland and scrub, usually nesting in soil and rotting wood, though a few species live in arboreal cavities in tropical rain forest (
Brown and Wilson 1959
; 
Bolton 2000
). Besides the most common form of reproductive females (gyne) some species of 

Strumigenys

have the ergatoid forms (
Silva and Brandão 2014
). Species of the genus are predators of Collembola, mites, insect larvae, and other small arthropods (
Wilson 1953
; 
Hölldobler and Wilson 1990
; 
Bolton 1999
; 
Kaufmann et al. 2003
), although, some few species occasionally feed on sugary substances (
Brown and Wilson 1959
). To capture their prey, some species use a kinetic mode of attack (
Gronenberg 1996
; 
Bolton 1999
).

